# Snyk policy file
# https://snyk.io/docs/using-snyk-policy/
version: v1.25.1
ignore:
  # Re-triaged on 2026-04-08 against the live repo state.
  # Backend now resolves mysql-connector-j 9.6.0, Tomcat 11.0.20,
  # Spring Framework 7.0.6, and Spring Security 7.0.4, so the previous
  # backend ignores were stale and have been removed.
  # Frontend npm audit is currently clean; only the remaining infra exceptions
  # still require Snyk policy coverage.
  SNYK-CC-TF-73:
    - 'modules/lambda/main.tf > resource > aws_security_group[lambda] > egress[0]':
        reason: >-
          Lambda must reach third-party HTTPS endpoints (Telegram, WhatsApp,
          and the AI provider) through the NAT gateway, so the remaining
          443 egress cannot be reduced to fixed CIDR ranges without a broader
          outbound proxy or firewall redesign. Revisit when controlled egress
          infrastructure is introduced.
        expires: '2026-07-02T00:00:00.000Z'
  SNYK-CC-TF-45:
    - 'modules/s3/main.tf > input > resource > aws_s3_bucket[access_logs] > logging':
        reason: >-
          This bucket is the dedicated destination for S3 access logs from the
          application buckets. AWS treats the log-delivery bucket as the sink,
          so requiring another logging target would create a recursive logging
          design rather than add useful audit coverage. Revisit if we introduce
          a separate centralized audit-log archive bucket.
        expires: '2026-07-02T00:00:00.000Z'
  SNYK-CC-TF-127:
    - 'modules/s3/main.tf > resource > aws_s3_bucket_versioning[audio_versioning] > versioning_configuration > mfa_delete':
        reason: >-
          AWS documents that MFA Delete can only be enabled by the bucket owner
          root account via CLI or API, and it cannot be used with S3 lifecycle
          configurations. These buckets intentionally use lifecycle retention
          rules, so this is not remediable as a normal Terraform change.
          Revisit only if lifecycle policies are removed and a manual root-only
          enablement process is acceptable.
        expires: '2026-07-07T00:00:00.000Z'
    - 'modules/s3/main.tf > resource > aws_s3_bucket_versioning[frontend_versioning] > versioning_configuration > mfa_delete':
        reason: >-
          AWS documents that MFA Delete can only be enabled by the bucket owner
          root account via CLI or API, and it cannot be used with S3 lifecycle
          configurations. These buckets intentionally use lifecycle retention
          rules, so this is not remediable as a normal Terraform change.
          Revisit only if lifecycle policies are removed and a manual root-only
          enablement process is acceptable.
        expires: '2026-07-07T00:00:00.000Z'
    - 'modules/s3/main.tf > resource > aws_s3_bucket_versioning[access_logs_versioning] > versioning_configuration > mfa_delete':
        reason: >-
          AWS documents that MFA Delete can only be enabled by the bucket owner
          root account via CLI or API, and it cannot be used with S3 lifecycle
          configurations. These buckets intentionally use lifecycle retention
          rules, so this is not remediable as a normal Terraform change.
          Revisit only if lifecycle policies are removed and a manual root-only
          enablement process is acceptable.
        expires: '2026-07-07T00:00:00.000Z'
patch: {}
